post_text:
The COVID-19 pandemic is a national crisis that poses a serious health risk for everyone. The health, safety, and well-being of our students, staff, and families is a top priority for Haysville USD 261.
Haysville USD 261 has and will continue to follow the guidance of federal, state, and county experts regarding the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. This includes the state's guidelines regarding wearing of masks, social distancing, and frequent hand washing. These guidelines have been put in place for schools to support the health and well-being of students and staff while continuing to provide academic excellence in a safe and caring environment.

We have created a page for updated information regarding our plans, procedures, and guides on how we plan to have our students safely return to our schools and learn. Click the link below ⬇️ to find information regarding our plans from masks, resources, and academic models.

http://www.usd261.com/ReturnToLearn/

post_text:
Parents we are asking that you know the signs and symptoms that may indicate that your child has COVID-19 before you send them to school. While the symptoms listed below are common, COVID-19 may present in other ways. If your child is not feeling well for any reason please keep them home. A health staff member will contact you to discuss your child's symptoms and determine how long your child should stay home.

Symptoms include:
Temperature 100.4 or higher
Sore throat
New uncontrolled cough that causes difficulty in breathing
Diarrhea, vomiting, or abdominal pain
New onset of severe headache
Loss of the sense of smell or taste

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact Beth Schutte, RN District School Nurse at 554-2200 or email at bschutte@usd261.com. Also, for other guidelines, and resources, click the link below.

http://www.usd261.com/ReturnToLearn/resources.php

If your student will be using an inhaler at school we encourage you to consider sending a spacer device as well. This spacer helps get all of the medication into your child's lungs and be most effective. If your student has not used a spacer before our health staff will be happy to help them learn how to use one.

A spacer cannot be used with all inhalers, so check with your pharmacist or school health staff if you have questions. If you have any other questions or concerns please contact Beth Schutte, RN District School Nurse at 554-2200, or email at bschutte@usd261.com.

School Lunch Update

All students will receive free lunch and breakfast meals beginning September 10 thru December 31. Remote learners will be provided with meals for the week. Parents of remote students will have to fill out a meal reservation form to specify their pick-up location. The form must be submitted every week in order to pick-up your student's meals. However, parents who qualify for free or reduced lunch must still fill out an application for the school year by September 20.

If you have questions or need help with reservations, please call food services at 316-554-2219.

Meal reservation form
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScD6g8KPQIk6raKt-t29Ha7iFMR2N757SizXVyBY0-rrRzKIg/viewform

Free or reduced lunch application

It is difficult to distinguish between cold symptoms and COVID-19 symptoms. Due to this, we will not be able to administer any over the counter cough and cold medications at school this year. We don't want to suppress what could be COVID-19 symptoms and place students or staff at risk. Allergy medications, such as Claritin and Benadryl, may be given for allergy symptoms.

If you have any questions or concerns about services available, please contact Beth Schutte, RN District School Nurse at 554-2200 or email at bschutte@usd261.com .

post_text:
When you send your child to school with his or her mask, we want them to be as safe and protected as possible. Here are a few tips to think about as school approaches.

M = A multi-layered mask made of cotton is best. This type of mask will protect you better than a mask with a valve or a neck gaiter.

A = Avoid your face. Never touch the front of your mask. Use the ear loops or straps to put on and remove the mask

S = Send more than one mask to school. Your child's mask may become soiled during the school day. It is important to have a back up to make sure your child is as protected as possible.

K = Keep your mask and your hands clean. If your mask becomes dirty or wet it is time to change your mask. Wash your hands often.

Click the link for more health resources. ⬇️
http://www.usd261.com/ReturnToLearn/resources.php

One of the best ways to help prevent the spread of germs is washing your hands with soap and water. Be sure to lather up for 20 seconds, about the amount of time it takes to sing "Happy Birthday". This would be a great time to bust out that creativity and have your kiddos make up their own song. When you can't use soap and water a hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol will do, just make sure you rub your hands until the hand sanitizer is dry.

Below is a link to some videos and fun experiments you can do with your kids to help promote handwashing. Keep 'em clean everyone! 💦🧼

http://www.usd261.com/ReturnToLearn/resources.php

post_text:
NEW TEMPERATURE GUIDELINES🌡

Traditionally we have sent students home with a temperature of 100 degrees or higher. In reviewing guidelines from the CDC, American Academy of Pediatrics, and the National Association of School Nurses, we found that the indication of fever should be 100.4 degrees. To bring us in line with these recommendations, we have changed our guideline for fever to a temperature of 100.4 or greater.

If you have any questions, you contact the District Nurses office at (316) 554-2200.
http://www.usd261.com/HealthServices/index.php

This afternoon, Governor Laura Kelly announced that she would be signing an Executive Order on Monday, July 20, delaying the start of schools in Kansas until after Labor Day.
District and building administrators have been working this past week on a plan for reopening schools that will focus on ensuring that all students and staff are safe while experiencing high quality teaching and learning.
Once we have Board of Education approval, we will be sending out a new school calendar that will reflect the later start date. As always, thank you for your patience during this time of uncertainty.

post_text:
Campus High School summer conditioning and activities has had the potential of exposure to Covid-19 to some students participating in a sports activity off grounds of Campus High. With that potential exposure, the requirement for any students participating in summer conditioning at Campus High School must be put on hold for a fourteen (14) day period. Strength and conditioning activities and all scheduled activities that include any students with participation in the strength and conditioning programs are suspended from occurring until July 10, 2020.

While we feel that the potential for any student-athlete getting Covid-19 remains extremely low, we take these precautions to continue to protect our student-athletes and staff health. Any student-athlete who experiences Covid-19 symptoms is encouraged to contact their physician for guidance or testing.

We are excited and honored to announce this year's nominees for the Kansas Teacher of the Year Award 🍎! Our first nominee is Amber Dougan, the technology teacher at Oatville Elementary. Our second nominee is Jacob Ditton, a history teacher at Campus High School. Help us congratulate them on their nomination!

The Kansas Teacher of the Year Award recognizes and utilizes representatives of excellent teaching in the elementary and secondary classrooms of the state. Its mission is to build and utilize a network of exemplary teachers who are leaders in the improvement of schools, student performance and the teaching profession.

For more information, click the link below.
https://www.ksde.org/Agency/Fiscal-and-Administrative-Services/Communications-and-Recognition-Programs/Kansas-Teacher-of-the-Year-Awards

We are excited to announce that Kansas teachers, students and parents just got a new partner in their continuous learning efforts. Thanks to the support of Kansas Public Broadcasters, Kansas students will receive supplemental education content by way of a new television program produced by Kansas PBS stations and KSDE, and hosted by local teachers. The new program called Learning Across Kansas will begin airing the week of April 20.

Each 30-minute segment, individually produced for elementary, middle school and high school students, will feature grade-specific educational content delivered by our very own Kansas teachers who serve on KSDE’s Continuous Learning Task Force.

A complete listing of program times is available here:

https://www.ksde.org/Agency/Fiscal-and-Administrative-Services/Communications-and-Recognition-Programs/Learning-Across-Kansas

post_text:
Come see Campus High School Mane Stage Players' double feature of Mockingbird and Booby Trap. Booby Trap by Ed Monk set in the near future. An American soldier sits in a combat zone, trapped by a landmine. As he waits to see what will happen to him, scenes from his past, present, and future unfold around him.

Mockingbird is adapted by Julie Jensen from the National Book Award-winning novel by Kathryn Erskine. It centers around Caitlin, an 11-year-old girl who is autistic. She has always relied on her older brother to help make sense of the world. When Devon is killed in a school shooting, she and her father must come to terms with their life alone and together. With the help of those around her, she learns how to get close to other people in spite of the “messiness” of emotions. We experience this play from Caitlin’s point of view.
Produced by permission of Playscripts Inc. and Dramatic Publishing.

Get your tickets here 👇
www.chsmanestage.booktix.com

Haysville West Middle School students will get the opportunity to practice using their green thumbs. 🌱 The school officially opened its new greenhouse with a ribbon-cutting.

The project was a collaboration between the district, middle school and with the help of a local nursery. Also, a special thanks to science teachers Shauna Tinich, Scott Peltier, and greenhouse expert Spencer Ring. STEM/STEAM students from all grade levels will have the chance to utilize the new greenhouse.

📸: [ribbon cutting, left to right] Ildo Martins (HWMS Principal); Ty Hamilton (HWMS Assistant Principal/Athletic Director); Paige Crum (BOE Vice-President); Susan Walston (BOE President); Dr. John Burke (Superintendent); Tom Gibson (BOE Member); Nicki McMullin ( HWMS Assistant Principal); Spencer Ring (local greenhouse guru).

post_text:
Congratulations to Campus High School's Amanda Phanivong & Michelle Kha for their scholarships they received from The Timothy P. O’Shaughnessy Foundation! 🥳🙌

The Foundation chooses scholars each year from a field of two candidates from each of 26 Wichita-area high-schools. Michelle Kha was a finalist for the Lifelong Learning Scholars award and won a $7,500 scholarship. Amanda Phanivong was the one of two students to receive the $100,000 scholarship from the foundation.

The Lifelong Learning Scholarship is designed to do more than pay for four years of college tuition; it encourages a lifetime full of educational pursuits, far beyond a bachelor’s degree. The Timothy P. O’Shaughnessy Foundation became the fifth private scholarship program in the nation that provides $100,000 or more in education funding for students. While the other programs are open to students nationally or internationally, the Foundation’s “Lifelong Learning Scholarship” is open exclusively to Wichita-area high-school seniors.

#usd261derful

Rex Elementary School - USD 261
November 13, 2019 at 8:00 PM ·

Congratulations to Michelle Groh for her nomination as a 2019-20 LifeChanger of the Year! The LifeChanger award recognizes K-12 school employees who make a positive difference in the lives of students.

Mrs. Groh's nomination also means that Rex Elementary is also in the running for a cash prize. In December, a committee will select 16 winners. The grand prize winner will win a $5,000 donation to the school and $5,000 personal award.

Thank you, Mrs. Groh, for all your hard work and dedication! Best of luck!

post_text:
Did you know that our AVID students are outperforming students nationally in FAFSA, college application completion and college acceptance?✨ Last year, 92% of USD 261 seniors participating in AVID completed a FAFSA application, compared to the national rate of 61%. Likewise, 100% of AVID students applied to a four-year college, and 96% were accepted. Nationally, 81% of high school students aspire to earn a bachelor’s degree yet less than 50% actually enroll at a four-year university.

We are proud of our students, staff, parents, partners, and everyone involved in the continued effort to prepare our students for college. Thank you!
